–1376","1325–1360":"1325–1360","1302–Female":"1302–Deceased","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1325":"1325","1302":"1302","about 1325":"about 1325","1453":"1453","1376":"1376","1360":"1360","1307":"1307","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Kirton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Kirton, Nottinghamshire, England","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"En","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Chinese: variant Romanization of the surname 任, based on its Mandarin pronunciation, see   Ren   1.","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surname 全, based on its pronunciation in Shanghai dialect, see   Quan   2.","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surname 曾, see   Zeng  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ren","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Wei, Yong, Hong, Hui, Chuan, Gang, Guang, Jian, Liang, Lihua, Ning, Qing, Chang, Min, Shen, Yiming.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 任, a term for women's rank of peerage in ancient Chinese: (i) it is said that the surname can be traced back to one of the 25 sons of the legendary Huang Di, the ‘Yellow Emperor’ (<i>c.</i> 27th century  BC ). (ii) from Ren (任), the name of an ancient state (located in Renxian in Hebei province) granted to Yu Yang, said to be a son or grandson of the legendary Huang Di, the ‘Yellow Emperor’ (<i>c.</i> 27th century  BC ). His descendants adopted the name of the state as their surname. (iii) from Ren (任), the name of a state (located in Shandong province) during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ).","English: variant of   Renn   2."]}]},{"name":"Blanco","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Manuel, Juan, Carlos, Jorge, Luis, Raul, Francisco, Miguel, Julio, Pedro, Jesus.","Spanish: nickname for a man with white or fair hair or a pale complexion, from <i>blanco</i> ‘white’.","Italian (Sicily): variant of   Bianco  , perhaps influenced by French <i>blanc</i> or Spanish <i>blanco</i> (see 1 above)."],"variants":[{"name":"Bianco","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Vito, Angelo, Salvatore, Carmine, Antonio, Rocco, Aniello, Francesco, Luca, Luigi, Pasquale, Sal.","Italian: from <i>bianco</i> ‘white’ (of ancient Germanic origin; compare Old High German <i>blanc</i> ‘bright, shining, white, beautiful’), originally applied as a nickname for a man with white or fair hair or a pale complexion, or for someone who habitually wore white, especially in jousting or other competitions, and later used as a personal name. Compare   Lo Bianco  ."]},{"name":"Blanca","meanings":["Spanish: from the feminine form of   Blanco   ‘white’."]}]},{"name":"Dama","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Mainly North American: of unknown origin, perhaps a transferred use of a surname that is fairly common in the United States. This may be of Irish origin, although the surname is not known in Ireland. <i>Dana</i> or <i>Ana</i> was the name of an ancient Irish fertility goddess, and this was also used in medieval times as a girl's name, However, it is not clear whether there is any connection between this name and the modern given name, which is sometimes also used as a feminine form of   Dan   or   Daniel .  Modern use as a boy's given name began in honour of  Richard Henry Dana  (  1815–82 ), author of Two Years before the Mast, who supported the rights of fugitive slaves before and during the Civil War. The popularity of the given name was increased by the fame of the film star  Dana Andrews  (  1909–92 )."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":13,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705192,"age":26,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705193,"age":35,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Dama En Blanco was born in 1302, in England. She had at least 1 daughter with William Loudham."},"et":{"1302–":"1302–Surnud","1307–1376":"1307–1376","1325–1360":"1325–1360","1302–Female":"1302–Surnud","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1325":"1325","1302":"1302","about 1325":"umbes 1325","1453":"1453","1376":"1376","1360":"1360","1307":"1307","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Kirton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Kirton, Nottinghamshire, England","England":"England"},"fi":{"1302–":"1302–Kuollut","1307–1376":"1307–1376","1325–1360":"1325–1360","1302–Female":"1302–Kuollut","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1325":"1325","1302":"1302","about 1325":"noin 1325","1453":"1453","1376":"1376","1360":"1360","1307":"1307","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Kirton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Kirton, Nottinghamshire, England","England":"England"},"fr":{"1302–":"1302–Décédée","1307–1376":"1307–1376","1325–1360":"1325–1360","1302–Female":"1302–Décédée","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1325":"1325","1302":"1302","about 1325":"environ 1325","1453":"1453","1376":"1376","1360":"1360","1307":"1307","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Kirton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Kirton, Nottinghamshire, Angleterre","England":"Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Dama En Blanco est née en 1302, à Angleterr